{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_011CcwM794qcZxCg4AYJu6v7","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"For-loops in bash come in a few flavors:\n\n**C-style (numeric):**\n```bash\nfor ((i = 0; i < 10; i++)); do\n  echo \"$i\"\ndone\n```\n\n**Over a list of words:**\n```bash\nfor name in alice bob carol; do\n  echo \"$name\"\ndone\n```\n\n**Over a numeric range** (brace expansion):\n```bash\nfor i in {1..5}; do\n  echo \"$i\"\ndone\n# with a step of 2:\nfor i in {0..10..2}; do\n  echo \"$i\"\ndone\n```\n\n**Over files** (globbing):\n```bash\nfor file in *.txt; do\n  echo \"$file\"\ndone\n```\n\n**Over command output / array:**\n```bash\nfor line in $(cat file.txt); do   # word-splits on whitespace\n  echo \"$line\"\ndone\n\narr=(one two three)\nfor item in \"${arr[@]}\"; do        # quote to preserve elements with spaces\n  echo \"$item\"\ndone\n```\n\nA couple of tips: always quote `\"$var\"` to avoid word-splitting surprises, and `do`/`done` can go on the same line as the header if you separate with `;` (as shown). Want an example for a specific use case?"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"cache_read_input_tokens":22619,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"afe04933-6b60-42e8-8823-a3cdcd9c9df3","uuid":"6cee0b7c-d90e-4b20-9a91-131ad6cc24b2","request_id":"req_011CcwM78CzhBS7Lqwokpspw"}
